<br>
Since we're talking radiative heating, I figured a first order approximation for the majority of the UF6 gas, not undergoing fission, but heated by the fission process, can be treated as a blackbody radiating due to its 25000K or 30000k temperature.  If this isn't true then that's good for the bulb<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> , but it makes sense that it should be valid. <br>
<br>
You can use the plank function to calculate the energy emitted at a given wavelength, since I don't know the spectral emissivity of UF6 I just calculated the pure blackbody curve, and summed the energies for the parts of the spectrum of interest, ie the infrared part where the absorption features are, and the extreme uv part.  Btw, I realized after my post that the additional amounts I gave in it were the total power and still needed to be divided by the surface area of the bulb, to get the heating rate, so the 10 to 20 MW/m^2 in the IR turns into .5 to 2 depending on the size of the bulb, so thats good.  But that also assumes the radiation is isotropic which I doubt.  And still presents a problem in the UV, and possibly the IR when all absorption features are accounted for.  The UV part is obviosly the possible showstopper, since the energy down there is much higher.<br>
<br>
Anyway to get the peak of the plank curve, you can just use wiens displacement law which gives the wavelength of peak intensity for a given Temperature.  Wiens law is simply<br>
Lambda max = 2898/T <br>
where lambda max is in microns<br>
and T is in kelvins.<br>
so for 25000K this gives Lmax = .116 microns or 116 nanometers<br>
and 30000K gives .097 um or 97 nanometers, so down in extreme uv or soft xrays.<br>
<br>
So the whole thing is based on treating the superheated core gas (non fissioning) as a plasma emitting as a blackbody (minus the spectral emissivity, which I don't know)<br>
<br>
the work I do tends to be concerned with more manegable temperatures in the atmosphere and I haven't done these calculations for things related to a GCNR, so that's where I'm not sure that the assumptions are necessarily correct, although I'd be surprised if they weren't.<br>
<br>
Again this was a first order approximation. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 241<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/17/03 5:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=211.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: bulb energy absorption</span><hr size=1> If I remember right it, the core of a GCNR only follows the blackbody curve for temperatures under 10000K. I found a conferance paper which listed values for higher temperatures. It is discussed in the &quot;here is a plan for a GCNR&quot; thread.<br>
