<br>
Well, the engines of the Liberty Ship, assuming we can figure out a way to make the darn things work, are VERY clean unless there is a fairly catastrophic failure.  Zero nuclides in the exhaust, zero radioactivity of any kind in the exhaust.  If you are TRULY paranoid about it, you can run it on pure hydrogen that has had the deuterium removed.  <br>
<br>
Also, given the gaseous fuel cycle I propose, all high level wastes are disposed of into space.  All squeaky clean!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>  How much thrust? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Thrust in an NTR is simply a factor of the power you can throw at your fuel mass.  More power means less fuel mass for more thrust, which is why I am trying to get the Liberty Ship as hot as I possibly can without melting the thing.<br>
<br>
That said, thrust is easy to get.  Isp is the tough thing.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 326<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/17/03 9:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=211.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: bulb energy absorption</span><hr size=1> If the isp is 3000+, that's fine!  27% fuel&amp;tankage is a great mass ratio!  Assuming a 60/40 structure/payload split, thats 30 tonnes per 100 tonnes of mass.  If you were to design it as an HTOL SSTO, you could make the spacecraft 600,000 kg (common airstrip mass), payload of 180 tonnes, and launcheable from any airstrip!<br>
